+# Distributed Rate Limiter Design
+
+This package implements two rate-limiting algorithms behind a shared interface
+and lets the same limiter run either in-process or against Redis. The goal is
+to keep the caller-facing API small while making the concurrency behavior
+explicit and dependable under load.
+
+## Components
+
+- `RateLimiter`: abstract API that exposes `enforce(key, cost=1)`.
+- `TokenBucketLimiter`: burst-friendly limiter with refill over time.
+- `SlidingWindowLimiter`: exact rolling-window limiter implemented as a log of
+  accepted events.
+- `Backend`: protocol used by the limiters for state access and atomic updates.
+- `InMemoryBackend`: lock-based single-process backend for local use and tests.
+- `RedisBackend`: Lua-backed distributed backend with atomic read-modify-write
+  logic.
+- `rate_limit(...)`: function decorator for sync and async call sites.
+- `RateLimitMiddleware`: ASGI middleware that applies enforcement per request
+  and emits standard rate-limit headers.
+
+## Request Flow
+
+The runtime path is intentionally shallow. The middleware or decorator resolves
+the key, calls `limiter.enforce`, and receives a `Decision` that contains the
+allow/deny outcome together with metadata needed for headers or exception
+handling.
+
+```mermaid
+flowchart LR
+    A[Request or function call] --> B[Decorator / ASGI middleware]
+    B --> C[RateLimiter.enforce(key, cost)]
+    C --> D[Backend atomic operation]
+    D --> E[Decision]
+    E --> F[Allow path with headers]
+    E --> G[Deny path with retry metadata]
+```
+
+At the limiter layer, the algorithm choice determines how state is interpreted:
+
+- Token bucket stores the current token balance and the last refill timestamp.
+- Sliding window stores exact accepted timestamps inside the active window.
+
+The backend is responsible for making the update atomic for a single key. This
+is the critical correctness boundary. If two workers race on the same key, the
+backend must serialize the state transition so both limiters see a consistent
+view.
+
+## Token Bucket Path
+
+Token bucket is used when short bursts are acceptable. The limiter computes how
+many tokens should have been replenished since the last update, caps the bucket
+at capacity, and then attempts to spend the requested `cost`. If enough tokens
+exist, the request is allowed and the updated balance is written back.
+
+This algorithm uses compact state and has a natural “burst + steady refill”
+behavior. It is a good fit for API traffic where smoothing is more important
+than exact “N requests in the last T seconds” semantics.
+
+The implementation returns:
+
+- `remaining`: floor of the remaining token balance;
+- `retry_after_ms`: how long until the requested cost can be satisfied;
+- `reset_ts`: when the bucket will be fully replenished if no more traffic
+  arrives.
+
+## Sliding Window Path
+
+Sliding window is used when exact rolling-window semantics matter. This package
+uses a log of accepted events rather than an approximate counter. Each accepted
+request contributes one or more cost units inside the current period. Before a
+new decision, the backend prunes entries older than `now - period`. The request
+is allowed only if the retained total plus `cost` remains within capacity.
+
+The log-based approach costs more than a counter because hot keys retain more
+entries and require pruning work. That tradeoff is deliberate. It guarantees the
+strong invariant that no key is granted more than `capacity` units in any true
+rolling window of length `period_ms`.
+
+For denials, retry timing is computed from the oldest accepted entries that must
+expire before enough capacity is freed. This produces exact retry timing instead
+of an estimate.
+
+## Backend Design
+
+`InMemoryBackend` is straightforward: it keeps Python dictionaries keyed by
+`(namespace, key)` and uses a per-key `threading.Lock` to serialize updates.
+This is sufficient for tests and single-process workloads, but it is not shared
+across processes.
+
+`RedisBackend` is the distributed implementation. Each algorithm is encoded as a
+Lua script so the full decision runs as one Redis-side atomic unit:
+
+- token bucket script reads state, computes refill, decides, writes state, and
+  sets TTL;
+- sliding window script prunes expired entries, counts retained entries,
+  decides, appends accepted timestamps, and sets TTL.
+
+Using Lua avoids lost-update races that would otherwise occur if multiple
+clients read and wrote the same key with separate commands. It also avoids the
+retry loops that a `WATCH` / `MULTI` / `EXEC` design would require under heavy
+contention.
+
+## Time and Clock Skew
+
+A distributed limiter should not trust every application process to have the
+same local clock. The Redis backend therefore uses Redis server time as the time
+source for enforcement calls. This keeps workers aligned even when application
+nodes drift slightly. The in-memory backend uses local process time because it
+is explicitly single-process and test-oriented.
+
+The returned `reset_ts` values are therefore backend-observed timestamps rather
+than caller-generated estimates.
+
+## Failure Modes
+
+The main failure modes are:
+
+- Redis unavailable or timing out;
+- hot-key contention causing high Redis CPU for sliding-window pruning;
+- large costs producing large event fan-out for the exact sliding log;
+- caller key functions raising errors or producing poor key cardinality.
+
+The package takes a conservative default stance. The decorator and raw limiter
+APIs propagate backend errors. The middleware also fails closed by default, which
+is the safer operational posture when rate limiting protects a scarce resource.
+
+## Degradation Strategy
+
+When Redis is unreachable, there are two reasonable policies:
+
+- fail closed: reject the request path because quota cannot be verified;
+- fail open: allow traffic to continue and accept possible overrun.
+
+This package exposes that choice in the ASGI middleware through `fail_open`.
+Defaulting it to `False` makes the safe path explicit. If an application values
+availability over strict protection, it can opt into `fail_open=True`. The raw
+limiter classes do not silently degrade to local memory because that would split
+distributed state and create misleading enforcement behavior across instances.
+
+The operational recommendation is:
+
+- use `RedisBackend` for shared production quotas;
+- monitor Redis latency and error rate;
+- reserve `fail_open=True` for endpoints where service continuity matters more
+  than quota precision;
+- prefer token bucket for extremely hot keys when bounded Redis cost is more
+  important than exact rolling-window semantics.
